I'm in the process of writing an article on this right now that I will post later, but this graph is pretty extraordinary. 

It show the distribution of the following quantity:

log(P2/P2) / log(t2/t1) ,

where P2 is the price of Bitcoin today and P1 the price of Bitcoin yesterday, t2 is the time from the Genesis Block today and t1 the time of the Genesis Block yesterday. In other words log(P2/P1) is the log of the returns a very important quantity in understanding financial assets. 

It turns out that this quantity is a sort of "invariant" in average. 

It is a random distribution but the mean is the slope of the power law that we observe over the general trajectory (about 6). 

What is the interpretation of this? Basically every day we have a mini power law with a random slope but in average over all these years, this value is the overall power law. Almost like domains in a magnet that are randomly oriented but their general mean points in one direction. 

This is the key to understand why the price seems locally random but it follows overall a precise power law. This shows the power law is a much more profound property of the system that at first appears. 

It works "in average" at all scales. As a real scale invariant system should do. 
I didn't try smaller scales than days so far but I will soon. This works for years, months, weeks, days, probably will work all the way to hours and minutes. 

It is incredible that Bitcoin has both a deterministic component log(t2/t1) and a random one log(P2/P1) but when they combine they form an invariant (even if just in average) that has been true over 15 years and 8 orders of magnitude. 

The theoretical distribution in red here is a Laplacian with mu=5.895 and parameter b=54.

Update on my Credit Cycle Indicators and Why I Flipped Bullish Last Weeküëá:

My overarching belief is that Bitcoin and crypto are risk assets, primarily driven by liquidity and appetite for risk. I've spent much of this year building indicators to find the best proxies for these factors, mainly focusing on the credit market.

These tools, combined with technicals for execution, have helped me navigate the past six months of chop in both directions relatively stress-free.

I use these tools to guide my market swings, and you'll see me reference them in my analysis.

With that in mind, let's dive into some key developments from last week that made me flip bullish:

1) Significant Upside Breakout in HY

The most notable event was a strong move in High Yield (HY), breaking out of the wedge we initially observed (https://t.co/wkk6fXfXgK).

Earlier in August, HY defended its 100-day MA from above during the volatility event. As of now, it has bounced back strongly and remains comfortably above both the 100- and 200-day MAs. From a technical perspective, I see no reason for this trend to reverse anytime soon.

I deem this significant because investors accepting lower yields for the same level of risk suggests increased market confidence, which is bullish risk.

Historically, sustained moves higher in HY have not coincided with sustained Bitcoin downtrends. 

If bearish bitcoin here, you must ask‚Äîis this time different? I lean towards no.

2) Credit Cycle Indicator Spiking Higher

In the same chart, you can see my credit cycle indicator spiking sharply, similar to what we saw in November 2023 and January 2024. Historically, Bitcoin tends to react positively to these bullish impulses. This adds another layer of confidence in a risk-on move. Confluence builds conviction, and these are solid green flags.

3) Credit Cycle Momentum Flipping Bullish (4h & 1d)

To dig deeper into trends, I use the delta between the short and long MAs of my credit cycle indicator. This helps me assess trend momentum and provides further confluence when taking positions.

I refer to the 4-hour as the "spark" and the 1-day as the "fuel." The spark can ignite a move but can‚Äôt sustain it without the fuel.

In Q1, the spark was ignited, and fuel provided support, leading to a sustained rally. However, we saw a spark without fuel in May, resulting in a short-lived move.

Now, for the first time since Q1, the spark seems to be supported by fuel. This setup fundamentally differs from the other rallies we've seen in the past six months, which is why I believe it's significant.

Execution

Thursday's sell-off rattled a few people. Equities, gold, and HY all rallied whilst bitcoin sold off; timeline full of bear porn.

However, given all the above data, I wanted to add to positions. The 57k level has been a key support level during this six-month range, so a test from above was critical.

I saw a sweep of stops at 57k, followed by a clear reclaim as an excellent spot to add to my position, and so I did.

Concluding

My bullish thesis will be invalidated if:
1) We see significant changes in the risk proxies and indicators I've outlined above.
2) We close below last week's wick at 56k.

Until then, I remain comfortably long. My base case is that we'll be much higher in a month.
